{% block tab_content %}
<div class="report">
    <p class="lede">Tables (and the more interactive <a href="datatable">datatables</a>) allow the presentation of tabular data. For the table layout pattern, you’ll likely want to use a datatable instead of a basic table.</p>

    <p>Because of the sheer amount of markup that tables can contain they're one of the only components where the styling is applied largely to element selectoirs. You do, however, need the <code>.table</code> class on the <code>&lt;table&gt;</code> element.

    {{ docs.heading('h2', 'Basic usage') }}

    {{ docs.example({
        html: "<table class=\"table\">" ~ tableBody ~ "</table>"
    }) }}

    {{ docs.heading('h3', 'Table captions') }}

    <p>Use the <code>caption</code> element to describe a table in the same way you would use a heading. A caption helps users find, navigate and understand tables. You can hide the visually hide the caption while keeping it accessible and visible to screen readers by adding the <code>hide</code> class.</p>

    {{ docs.heading('h3', 'Table headers') }}

    <p>Use table headers to tell users what the rows and columns represent. Use the scope attribute to help users of assistive technology distinguish between row and column headers.</p>

    {{ docs.heading('h2', 'Width options') }}
    {{ docs.heading('h3', 'Full width') }}

    <p>Tables can use the full available width of the parent container by adding the <code>.table--full</code> class on the <code>&lt;table&gt;</code> element.</p>

    {{ docs.example({
        html: "<table class=\"table table--full\">" ~ tableBody ~ "</table>"
    }) }}

    {{ docs.heading('h3', 'Fixed width') }}

    <p>Tables will automatically resize their columns depending on the column widths and the available space. You can override this behaviour, and make columns equal width, by adding the <code>.table--fixed</code> class on the <code>&lt;table&gt;</code> element.</p>

    {{ docs.example({
        html: "<table class=\"table table--full table--fixed\">" ~ tableBody ~ "</table>"
    }) }}

    {{ docs.heading('h2', 'Horizontal scroll') }}

    <p>When dealing with user-supplied content and responsive design it's not possible to guarantee the table can nicely accommodate all content in the space available. For large tables it’s a good idea to allow the table to scroll horizontally when the content exceeds the viewport.

